Structured Queury Language:
- the way we communicate to databases
- uses clauses to create a statement
- sql keywords are not case sensitive; SELECT & select is the same

Basic Concepts (COMMANDS) in SQL:
- SELECT -> choose columns to display
- UPDATE -> updates data in a database
- DELETE -> deletes data from a database
- FROM -> choose table where you're looking at
- WHERE -> filter data (rows)
- GROUP BY -> allows you to group your data's in rows
- HAVING BY -> filter GROUPED rows (NOT RAW datas)
- ORDER BY -> allows you to sort your data

ADDITIONAL:
- INSERT INTO -> inserts new data into a database
- CREATE DATABASE -> creates a new database
- ALTER DATABASE -> modify changes in a database
- CREATE TABLE -> add a new table
- ALTER TABLE -> allows modification in a table
- DROP TABLE -> deletes entire table
- CREATE INDEX -> makes a search key (index) 
- DROP INDEX -> deletes a search key
- LIMIT -> allows you to put a specific number of data that will be displayed
- COUNT -> number of data's that meets the condition specified
- DISTINCT -> allows you to view a unique value (distinct)

Syntax:
- some requires the use of semicolon at the end of each sql statement
- annotations matter as they simplify code by doing things automatically.

JPA / HIBERNATE Concepts (Object-relational Mapping):
- they serve as a tool that automatically converts your JAVA Objects and DATABASE TABLES so you dont have to write SQL queries manually for basic operations

Commonly Used Annotations:

- ENTITY -> a java class that prepresents a table in your databases
- ID -> this shows the unique or primary key (usually followed by auto-incrementation)
- ONE-TO-MANY; MANY-TO-ONE -> relationship status (can be between user and application)
- COLUMN -> customization the properties of a column
- GENERATEDVALUE -> auto-increment
- JOINCOLUMN -> foreign key references
